Accounting break-even refers to the point wherein the company makes exactly zero revenue. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC+D}}{\text{P - v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed cost}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Depreciation}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
\text{v}&=\text{Variable price per unit}
\end{aligned}$$

The cash break-even point refers to the point wherein the cashflow is exactly zero. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{P-v}}
\end{aligned}$$

The financial break-even is the point wherein the net present value (NPV) is exactly zero. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC + OCF}}{\text{P - v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where OCF = Initial cost since the NPV is zero

The degree of operating leverage refers to how much the company's income is affected by the change in sales. This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{DOL}&=1+\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{OCF}}
\end{aligned}$$
